What is the Moscow Treaty on Strategic Offensive Reductions? The Moscow Treaty on Strategic Offensive Reductions (SORT), also called the Treaty on Measures for the Further Reduction and Limitation of Strategic Offensive Arms, was an agreement between the United States and the Soviet Union signed in Moscow on July 8, 1991. The treaty called for the elimination of all nuclear and conventional missiles, launchers, and bombers by the year 2012. The treaty eliminated all nuclear and conventional missiles, launchers, and bombers by the year 2012. The treaty was signed after the collapse of the Soviet Union, and was intended to reduce the threat of nuclear war.
